<h2>HVAC Systems in Florida</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Florida's subtropical and tropical climate creates unique challenges for HVAC systems that must operate efficiently in high heat and humidity conditions for extended periods. The state's cooling season typically runs from April through October, with some areas requiring air conditioning year-round. Average summer temperatures range from 85-95¬∞F, with humidity levels often exceeding 70%, creating heat index values that can reach well over 100¬∞F.</p>

<p>The combination of high temperatures and humidity means that HVAC systems in Florida must not only cool the air but also remove substantial moisture to maintain indoor comfort. This dual requirement places additional demands on equipment and makes proper sizing and efficiency ratings particularly important. Undersized systems will struggle to maintain comfort during peak conditions, while oversized systems may not run long enough to adequately dehumidify the air.</p>

<p>Hurricane and severe weather considerations also play a role in HVAC system selection for Florida homes. Equipment must be designed to withstand high winds, and outdoor units should be properly secured and positioned to minimize storm damage. Additionally, the salt air in coastal areas requires equipment with enhanced corrosion resistance to ensure long-term durability and performance.</p>

